var e=`# CHAPTER 6 — The Primordial

The flames started small.

Two ignition points on Kim's back, where Yawanari's fingers had rested last. Black, without visible heat, moving with a slowness that didn't belong to fire. They looked more like smoke that had decided to take shape.

Thunderbolt took a second step back.

The crowd that had gone quiet went quiet in a different way.

The flames climbed Kim's shoulders. Where they touched skin, geometric lines woke up, rising along his neck and falling down his arms like rivers finding their own bed for the first time. His hair was the last to change, strand by strand lengthening, black turning white from the root.

Kim stood up.

The knee that had given out held his weight without protest. The fractured fingers closed and opened slowly, testing. Kim looked at his own hands with the expression of someone running through an inventory.

— It's been a while. — Low, to himself.

The words came out in Kim's voice, but carried another frequency underneath — something older inhabiting his vocal cords like a tenant who arrived before the building was built.

Thunderbolt materialized his spear, but it was an unthinking act, survival instinct surfacing on its own.

— This doesn't change anything. — More to himself than to Kim. He needed to believe that.

The lightning came. Kim Ancestral didn't dodge. He raised an open hand and the bolt dissipated on contact with the black flames like water hitting embers. The flames grew slightly.

As if they had eaten.

Thunderbolt looked at the spear in his own hand.

---

In the stands, Jack was on his feet with both hands on the railing. The expression on his face had shifted again, passing through terror and arriving somewhere that had no direct name. He had known Kim since they were twelve. He had seen Kim hit, get hit, laugh, cry exactly once and pretend it hadn't happened — he would never admit it, but it happened. He knew every variation of posture, every microexpression.

The thing standing in the center of the arena wore Kim's face. Maybe his body. But that was not Kim.

---

Kim Ancestral walked toward Thunderbolt with steps that had no urgency whatsoever.

Thunderbolt activated his special ability — SHAMAN — and called it out fast.

His spear began its transformation, becoming pure blue electric energy. He leapt onto that energy and was consumed by it, dissolving into a speed far beyond the first attack — the blue blur that had destroyed Kim forty minutes ago. Strikes arriving from impossible angles, electricity crackling between impacts, the entire arena lit in pulses of electric blue. This was the move that had earned one thousand two hundred victories. This was everything Thunderbolt had.

Kim Ancestral stood still at the center of all of it.

Every strike landed. Every strike was absorbed by the flames, which grew with each contact. The blue blur increased its speed — more hits per second, more electricity discharging — and the flames answered, growing larger, denser, their edges beginning to take on a shape that was not the shape of fire.

Thunderbolt slowed, apparently drained, the electricity around his body weak, as if it had been consumed.

For the first time in one thousand two hundred battles he had used everything and the opponent was still standing. The flames had doubled in size. And at their edges, for a second Thunderbolt didn't want to believe he saw, something moved with its own purpose. A shape that had a neck. That had a jaw.

— What is that. — The voice small.

Kim Ancestral tilted his head to the side.

— Your taste is revolting. It is beneath me to feed on something like you.

Thunderbolt pulled two energy discs from the shoulders of his armor — emergency resources saved for tournament finals. He launched them in trajectories that would cross at the point where Kim Ancestral stood.

The flames engulfed them before impact.

---

On impact, a dense smoke emerged — not from Thunderbolt's powers, but radiating from Kim Ancestral himself. Something ancient, dark, forgotten was being born.

It wasn't gradual like the first transformation. It was rupture.

Kim Ancestral's skin darkened as the markings overflowed from within, tribal geometric patterns taking over his entire body until no surface remained without a symbol. The black leather coat materialized over his shoulders, feathers and bones at the edges, the fabric absorbing the light around it. His eyes lost what remained of their irises, becoming white spheres that reflected nothing.

And the flames took shape.

They were no longer flames. They were creatures made of black fire, serpents of darkness coiled around Kim Primordial's arms with the familiarity of animals recognizing their owner. At the edges of the largest one, a jaw opened and closed slowly. In the second largest, the silhouette of a long neck. In the third, wings that didn't exist but whose shadow did.

Hungry. With the patience of something that is going to eat regardless.

The arena went quiet in a way that was different from all the other silences of that day. It was the silence of people who have seen something they cannot name and know they will not forget.

---

Thunderbolt didn't move when Kim Primordial reached him.

Not out of bravery. Out of that second of paralysis that comes before understanding that no movement is possible.

Kim Primordial grabbed Thunderbolt's helmet and tore it off. The metal that had withstood hundreds of battles gave like wet paper.

Underneath was no human face.

It was stone. A face carved in dark granite, every feature sculpted with precision, eyes that were deep slits, mouth a straight line.

Except the slits were now open wider than the granite allowed, forced by something coming from inside. Whatever was inside Thunderbolt's stone avatar was very, very afraid.

— So this is how you live inside that disgusting shell. — Kim Primordial examined the stone face with antiquarian curiosity.

The first punch landed on the cheekbone with a precision that wasn't anger. It was methodology. The same way Thunderbolt had worked Kim's face forty minutes ago — mapping the damage, calculating the next point.

Thunderbolt tried to activate his spear. Kim Primordial caught the wrist before the discharge could leave and twisted slowly, the avatar's bones protesting in sequence like notes on a descending scale until the spear dropped.

— No, no. The meal will behave at feeding time.

Punch to the side of the jaw. The granite shifted, Thunderbolt spat blood and a fragment of stone. Punch to the nose, stone cartilage giving with a dry crack. Punch to the eyebrow, the surface splitting, blood running down the face in a red curtain.

Thunderbolt tried to defend himself. His arms came up by instinct. Kim Primordial took one, twisted it back until the shoulder left its socket with the same definitive sound Rock had made in the annex. Thunderbolt collapsed to his knees.

— Look at me, worm. Be the lesser creature you are and beg for your life. — Kim Primordial crouched down to speak at the level of Thunderbolt's destroyed face.

Thunderbolt raised his face, in tears, bleeding, holding his dislocated shoulder.

— Mercy. I beg you. Enough, I give up. You won. Take the money, take the victory, take everything. Let's just end this match. I beg you.

Kim Primordial opened his arms. An animalistic, ancestral roar left his throat like that of an ancient emperor of beasts. The entire crowd froze — not understanding, but something inside each of them feared, made them fear as they had never feared anything in their lives.

Kim Primordial beat his chest and roared, a creature in celebration, in demonstration of its superiority.

He lifted Thunderbolt by the throat with one hand. With the other, he drove a cross into the stomach that expelled all the air at once. Then a rising knee to the already-broken jaw. The impact this time wasn't surgical. It was termination.

Thunderbolt hanging in the air by his throat, no more useful movement left, feet swaying.

Kim Primordial examined him for a second with the expression of a cook checking the doneness.

— The meat has been properly tenderized. That should improve the taste of something so beneath me.

The black flame creatures descended his arms like intelligent liquid, advancing toward Thunderbolt with the slowness of something that has no rush because the prey is going nowhere.

Thunderbolt's scream was not from physical pain. It was before that. It was the scream of someone who feels something being removed from a place that has no anatomical name.

The creatures devoured slowly. That is how they work. They don't burn, they don't char. They consume, with the precision of something that has been denied food for a long time and finally has the meal in front of it.

— Do not resist. It lasts longer when you resist.

Thunderbolt resisted.

It lasted longer.

The crowd that had called for blood throughout the previous chapter was motionless. Some had looked away. Others couldn't look away. Jack had his eyes shut, fists on the railing.

The Narrator, for the first time since he had existed, said nothing.

---

When it was over, the space where Thunderbolt had been had a texture different from ordinary emptiness.

The Narrator approached with the steps of someone recalculating everything they knew about the work they do.

— He whom we took for a newcomer has proven to be an undeniable force. — The voice not entirely steady. — How do you wish to be proclaimed, champion?

Kim Primordial looked at the space where Thunderbolt had been. Then at the arena. Then at the extended microphone.

— I am The Primordial.

The arena sang the name.

*The Primordial. The Primordial. The Primordial.*

The ovation took the entire arena.

---

The first spasm came while the crowd was still shouting.

The black flame creatures retreated, restless, like animals sensing the tide turning. The white glow of his eyes flickered, went out, came back weaker. The tribal markings began to fade from the inside out, the most complex patterns disappearing first.

— No. — The voice different, something of Kim escaping through the edges. — That meal was insufficient. It only gave me minutes.

The Primordial phase reversed. The coat disappeared. The black fire creatures dissolved into smoke. The Ancestral phase reversed after. His hair darkened strand by strand. The tattoos faded in reverse order. The white eyes regained irises, then pupils.

Kim dropped to his knees.

---

The school annex came back all at once.

Cold concrete under his knees. Wind through the glassless window. The smell of mold and old cigarettes.

Kim was on his knees in the center of the annex with the SBI still on his head, his body drained in a way that had nothing to do with the damage from IF. It was exhaustion of a different kind, as if something had used his physical body as fuel without asking.

Freddy was on the floor three meters away, unconscious, the SBI still on his face.

Jack reached Kim exactly when his legs gave out, caught him before the floor could decide the outcome.

The two of them stayed on the floor together for a second that needed no words.

Kim tried to raise his right arm with clear intent.

— You don't have the strength to punch me right now, man.

— I know. But as soon as I do—

— I know. I know.

Kim leaned against his friend for one more second. Then pulled away, stayed on his knees, reached for the pack in his pocket. His fingers found the cigarette. He looked for the lighter.

Footsteps over the debris on the annex floor. Light, calculated, arriving right in the blind spot of his gaze.

Nina appeared through the glassless window with the ease of someone who knows the way, looked at the scene, at Freddy unconscious, at the five bodyguards still where they had fallen, at Kim on his knees with the cigarette between his lips waiting for a light.

She walked up to him, pulled the cigarette from Kim's mouth before the flame could catch, placed it between her own lips, lit it with her own lighter.

She inhaled.

Handed it back.

Looked at Kim for a long second, at the space of memory of what she had seen in the arena through her own SBI.

— Good fight.

Pause.

— You're Kim, right?

Another pause, shorter.

— Or do you prefer The Primordial?`;export{e as default};
